New code must follow this package layout. Do not put business logic in controllers or entities.

## Naming (English only)

- Classes, interfaces, enums, records, methods, fields, and parameters: **English**, `PascalCase` / `camelCase` as per Java conventions.
- REST paths and JSON property names: English, kebab-case or camelCase consistently (prefer camelCase in JSON to match Java records).
- Database table/column names: `snake_case` if mapped explicitly; otherwise follow JPA defaults.
- No Spanish identifiers in source code (comments in Spanish are allowed but prefer English for API-facing docs).

## Java 25 & Spring Boot practices

- Prefer **constructor injection** (explicit constructors; no field injection).
- Use `Optional` only as a return type from repositories/services, not in DTOs or controller parameters.
- Use `record` for immutable value types (DTOs, commands, queries, projections).
- Use `sealed` interfaces/classes when modeling closed domain hierarchies.
- Prefer `var` only when the type is obvious from the right-hand side.
- Validate input with Jakarta Bean Validation (`@Valid`, `@NotNull`, etc.) on request DTOs.
- Map Entity ↔ DTO in the service layer (or dedicated mapper), never expose entities from REST.
- Transactions: `@Transactional` on service methods, read-only when applicable.
- Repositories: extend `JpaRepository<Entity, Id>`; custom queries with `@Query` or method names.
- Controllers: thin — delegate to services; return `ResponseEntity<T>` when status/body vary.
- Exceptions: domain exceptions + `@RestControllerAdvice` with consistent error DTO (record).
- Configuration: externalize in `application.properties` / profiles; no secrets in source.
- Tests: `@SpringBootTest` for integration; slice tests (`@WebMvcTest`, `@DataJpaTest`) when focused.

## DTOs — Java records

- All API request/response types live under `dto/` as **records**.
- Name: `CreateReservationRequest`, `ReservationResponse`, etc.
- Compact constructors for validation when needed; use Jackson annotations only when JSON shape differs from record components.
- Do not use records for JPA entities.

```java
/**
 * Payload to create a new reservation.
 *
 * @param guestName guest full name
 * @param date      reservation date (ISO-8601)
 */
public record CreateReservationRequest(
        @NotBlank String guestName,
        @NotNull LocalDate date
) {}
```

## Javadoc (mandatory on public API)

Every **public** class, interface, enum, record, and **public** method must have up-to-date Javadoc:

- Summary sentence in English.
- `@param` for each parameter, `@return` when not void, `@throws` for declared/checked or documented runtime cases.
- Keep in sync when signatures change; remove stale tags.

```java
/**
 * Creates a reservation for the given request.
 *
 * @param request validated creation payload
 * @return the created reservation representation
 * @throws ReservationConflictException if the slot is unavailable
 */
public ReservationResponse createReservation(CreateReservationRequest request) {
    // ...
}
```

## REST & OpenAPI

- Annotate controllers for springdoc (`@Tag`, `@Operation`, `@ApiResponse`) on public endpoints.
- Use correct HTTP verbs and status codes (201 + `Location` on create, 204 on delete without body).
- Version APIs if needed (`/api/v1/...`).

## JPA entities

- `entity/` package; prefer explicit accessors over Lombok unless the project adopts it.
- `@Entity`, `@Table`, `@Id`, `@GeneratedValue`; equals/hashCode on business key or id only.
- Lazy associations by default; avoid `EAGER` unless justified.

## Code quality

- No wildcard imports; no unused code.
- Logging: SLF4J (`private static final Logger log = LoggerFactory.getLogger(...)`).
- Avoid `System.out.println` in production code.
- Match existing indentation (tabs in this project) and Spring Boot style.
